# Sample text to demonstrate text chunking

text = """Elias was a hoarder of memories. His shop, a cluttered labyrinth tucked at the end of a cobblestone alley, was a testament to his inability to let go. Every shelf sagged under the weight of tarnished pocket watches, faded sepia photographs, and dusty bound journals. To the casual observer, it was a junk shop. To Elias, it was a museum of unlived lives.His favorite part of the day was the quiet hour just before dawn. With a steaming mug of black coffee, he would sit at his workbench, the soft glow of a solitary desk lamp cutting through the gloom. It was during these moments that the shop felt alive, humming with the untold stories of a thousand forgotten objects.One rainy Tuesday, while clearing space on a shelf for a collection of vintage glass bottles, Elias noticed a small, intricately carved wooden box wedged behind a stack of old ledgers. He didn't remember acquiring it. It was made of dark mahogany, its surface polished smooth by time, and was sealed with a delicate silver latch.Brushing away the dust, Elias felt a strange sense of anticipation. The box felt unnaturally heavy in his hands, not with physical weight, but with something else. It vibrated with a faint, rhythmic pulse. He carefully unlatched the silver clasp and lifted the lid.Inside, resting on a bed of faded velvet, lay a brass compass. But this was no ordinary compass. The face was etched with unfamiliar symbols instead of the standard cardinal directions, and the needle, fashioned from what looked like polished bone, was spinning wildly. It didn't point north. It seemed to point inward, towards his chest.As Elias touched the compass, the mundane world seemed to slip away. The steady drone of the rain outside faded, replaced by a soft, melodic whispering. The symbols on the compass face began to glow with a soft, ethereal blue light. He felt a gentle tug, a pull not just on the compass, but on his very soul. It was a call, a summons to an adventure he had long buried beneath the weight of his routines.For years, Elias had been content to live vicariously through the objects he collected, observing life from the sidelines. But now, the compass was demanding that he become an active participant. It was urging him to step out of his comfort zone, to venture into the unknown.He closed the box, picked up his coat, and stepped out into the rainy morning. The compass, now safely tucked in his pocket, guided his steps. He walked through the awakening city, past familiar landmarks, towards the edge of town where the dense forest began.The whispering grew louder, a chorus of voices encouraging him forward. He walked for hours, the compass leading him deeper into the woods, away from the familiar and into the magical. He finally arrived at a clearing he had never seen before. In the center stood an ancient, magnificent oak tree, its branches reaching towards the sky.At the base of the tree was a small opening, just large enough for a person to enter. The compass in his pocket vibrated furiously, its light brighter than ever. Elias knelt down and peered into the opening. Inside, bathed in a pool of golden light, were dozens of small, glowing spheres. Each sphere contained a memory—not a memory of an object, but a memory of a feeling, a moment of joy, a spark of inspiration.Elias realized that the box and the compass were not just a collection of artifacts, but a key to unlocking the magic he had ignored for so long. He reached out and touched one of the spheres. Instantly, he was flooded with a wave of warmth, a memory of his own childhood, of a time when he believed in magic and possibility.He understood then that the true treasures of life were not things to be hoarded, but experiences to be felt, memories to be made, and moments of connection to be shared. The compass had not guided him to a hidden treasure, but to a deeper understanding of himself and the world around him.With a newfound sense of purpose, Elias gathered the glowing spheres and placed them in his pockets. He retraced his steps back to the city, the compass now quiet in his hand. His shop was the same as he had left it, but he was changed.He no longer saw the objects on his shelves as remnants of the past, but as reminders of the rich tapestry of life. He began to share the stories of the objects with his customers, connecting with them on a deeper level. The shop became a place of wonder, where people didn't just buy things, but found inspiration and connection.Elias had found his own magic, and in doing so, he brought a little bit of it into the lives of everyone who crossed his threshold. He continued to collect memories, but now he also helped create new ones. He understood that while the past was important, it was the present that truly mattered, and that every moment was an opportunity to write a new story."""

CHUNK_SIZE = 100

# Split the text into fixed-size character chunks
chunks = [
    text[i:i + CHUNK_SIZE]
    for i in range(0, len(text), CHUNK_SIZE)
]

# Print each chunk
for index, chunk in enumerate(chunks, start=1):
    print(f"\nChunk {index}\n{'-' * 20}")
    print(chunk)